[[File:Cmd640b.jpg|thumb|CMD 640b PCI IDE controller]] '''CMD640''', the California Micro Devices Technology Inc product 0640, is an [[AT Attachment|IDE]] interface chip for the [[Conventional PCI|PCI]] and [[VESA Local Bus|VLB]] buses. CMD640 had some sort of hardware acceleration: [[WDMA (computer)|WDMA]] and Read-Ahead (prefetch) support.
CMD Technology Inc was acquired by [[Silicon Image Inc.]] in 2001.
{| class="wikitable" |- !Chip !Protocol |- |SiI/CMD 640 |MDMA 1 |- |SiI/CMD 643 |MDMA 2 |- |SiI/CMD 646 |[[UDMA|UDMA 2]] |- |SiI/CMD 648 |UDMA 4 |- |SiI/CMD 649 |UDMA 5 |- |SiI0680 |UDMA 6 |}
== Hardware bug ==
The original CMD640 has a [[data corruption]] bug.<ref>[http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/drivers/ide/cmd640.c - linux/drivers/ide/pci/cmd640.c Version 1.02 Sep 01, 1996]</ref><!--These chips are basically fucked by design, and getting this driver to work on every motherboard design that uses this screwed chip seems bloody well impossible. However, we're still trying.--> The data corruption bug is similar to the bug affecting the contemporaneous PC Tech [[RZ1000]] chipset. Both chipsets were used on a number of motherboards, including those from [[List of Intel chipsets#Pentium chipsets|Intel]].
Мodern operating systems have a workaround for this bug by prohibiting aggressive acceleration mode and losing about 10% of the performance.
