{{COI|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox company | name = Episerver | type = Private | logo = [[File:Epi-logo-red-square.jpeg|frameless|Episerver Logo]] | foundation = [[Sweden]] (1994) | location_city = Nashua, NH USA and Stockholm, Sweden | key_people = Mark Duffell, President and CEO / James Norwood, Executive Vice President Strategy and CMO | industry = [[Software]] | parent =[[Accel-KKR]] | products = Episerver Digital Experience Cloud | homepage = https://www.episerver.com }}
'''Episerver''' is a global software company offering [[Web content management system|web content management (WCM)]] (or [[Content Management System|CMS]]), [[E-commerce|digital commerce]], and [[digital marketing]], through the Episerver Digital Experience Cloud software platform. Episerver also offers [[personalization]] through Peerius, a company acquired in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tamturk|first1=Venus|title=Episerver Buys Peerius to Boost Autonomous Personalization|url=http://www.cms-connected.com/News-Articles/August-2016/Episerver-Buys-Peerius-to-Boost-Autonomous-Persona|website=CMS Connected|publisher=CMS-Connected|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref>
== History == Episerver was founded in 1994 in Stockholm, Sweden, by Mikael Runhem. Then known as Elektropost Stockholm AB, the company focused on internet-based electronic mail. Elektropost Stockholm AB expanded to provide technology for building websites and introduced the first version of the EPiServer CMS platform in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Guseva|first1=Irina|title=Web CMS Vendor EPiServer Acquired by a Surprising Buyer|url=http://www.cmswire.com/cms/web-cms/web-cms-vendor-episerver-acquired-by-a-surprising-buyer-009167.php|website=CMSWire|publisher=Simpler Media Group, Inc.|accessdate=Nov 10, 2010}}</ref>
In 2002, the first version of EPiServer CMS that was based on [[Microsoft]]’s [[.NET Framework]], EPiServer CMS 4.0, was launched. In 2006, Mikael Runhem changed the company’s name to EPiServer AB. In 2007, the second .NET-based version of EPiServer CMS was launched, version 5.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}
In 2010, the company was owned by a group of investors, including Amadeus Capital, Martin Bjäringer, Monterro Holdings, Northzone Ventures, Mikael Runhem and family and employees. In November 2010, this group sold the company to [[IK Investment Partners]].<ref>{{cite web|title=IK Investment Partners acquires Episerver|url=http://www.episerver.com/about-us/pressroom/press-release-archive-2010/ik-investment-partners-acquires-episerver/|website=Episerver|accessdate=Nov 10, 2010}}</ref>{{Self-published inline|date=March 2018}}
In December 2014, IK Investment Partners sold Episerver to [[Accel-KKR]], a technology-focused private equity investment firm.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Backaitis|first1=Virginia|title=Not a Rumor: Accel-KKR Invests in Episerver|url=http://www.cmswire.com/cms/digital-marketing/not-a-rumor-accelkkr-invests-in-episerver-027418.php|website=CMSWIre|publisher=Simpler Media Group, Inc.|accessdate=Dec 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern-Peltz|first1=Mikkel|title=IK sells EPiServer to Accel-KKR|url=http://www.unquote.com/nordics/official-record/73218/ik-sells-episerver-to-accel-kkr|website=Unquote|publisher=Mergermarket Limited|accessdate=Dec 9, 2014}}</ref> Accel-KKR had also recently purchased Ektron, a Nashua, New Hampshire-based CMS company. In January 2015, Episerver and Ektron merged.<ref>{{cite web|title=Episerver and Ektron merge|url=http://www.kmworld.com/Articles/News/News/EPiServer-and-Ektron-merge-101724.aspx|website=KMWorld|publisher=Information Today Inc.|accessdate=Jan 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Seebacher|first1=Noreen|title=Told You So: Ektron is Merging with Episerver|url=http://www.cmswire.com/cms/web-cms/told-you-so-ektron-is-merging-with-episerver-027861.php|website=CMSWire|publisher=Simpler Media Group, Inc.|accessdate=Jan 27, 2015}}</ref> Two former executives from KANA Software, CEO Mark Duffell and CMO James Norwood, were appointed President and CEO and Executive Vice President Strategy and CMO of Episerver, respectively. Martin Henricson, CEO of the former Episerver business assumed the role of Executive Chairman for the merged entity.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}
The company combined its software into the Episerver Digital Experience Cloud,<ref>{{cite web|title=Episerver and Ektron merge and target the mid-market for digital experience|url=https://www.ovum.com/episerver-and-ektron-merge-and-target-the-mid-market-for-digital-experience/|website=Ovum|publisher=Informa PLC|accessdate=Feb 6, 2015}}</ref> and in June 2015, Episerver launched the first major release of its platform following the Ektron merger.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nicastro|first1=Dom|title=Episerver Taps Ektron Roots in New Release|url=http://www.cmswire.com/web-cms/episerver-taps-ektron-roots-in-new-release/|website=CMSWire|publisher=Simpler Media Group, Inc.|accessdate=Jun 4, 2015}}</ref> In November 2015, the company rebranded itself, changing EPiServer to Episerver, and including the shortened name “Epi”.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Backaitis|first1=Virginia|title=Episerver Tries to Rebuild its Brand|url=http://www.cmswire.com/web-cms/episerver-tries-to-rebuild-its-brand/|website=CMSWire|publisher=Simpler Media Group, Inc.|accessdate=Nov 16, 2015}}</ref>
In August 2016, Episerver acquired Peerius, a London UK-based commerce personalization company. The brand now is fully integrated as EpiPersonalization into the Episerver Platform. Former Peerius CEO Roger Brown left the company.
== Mergers and acquisitions == * March 1, 2012: Episerver acquired Mediachase, an e-commerce and collaboration software solutions provider.<ref>{{cite web|title=Episerver Acquires Business of e-Commerce Solution Provider Mediachase|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/episerver-acquires-business-e-commerce-140000324.html|website=Yahoo! Finance|publisher=Yahoo!|accessdate=Mar 12, 2012|ref=References}}</ref> * May 8, 2012: Episerver acquired 200OK AB, a Swedish enterprise search solutions provider.<ref>{{cite web|title=Episerver Acquires 200OK AB, an Enterprise Search Solution Provider|url=http://www.episerver.com/about-us/pressroom/press-release-archive-2012/episerver-acquires-200ok-ab-an-enterprise-search-solution-provider/|website=Episerver|accessdate=May 8, 2012|ref=References}}</ref>{{Self-published inline|date=March 2018}}<ref>{{cite web|last1=Berthiaume|first1=Dan|title=Episerver Scales for Big Data, Better Content Targeting With 200OK AB Acquisition|url=http://www.cmswire.com/cms/customer-experience/episerver-scales-for-big-data-better-content-targeting-with-200ok-ab-acquisition-015532.php|website=CMSWire|publisher=Simpler Media Group, Inc.|accessdate=May 10, 2012|ref=References}}</ref> * May 6, 2013: Episerver acquired Swedish search provider, Euroling.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Castro|first1=Marc|title=Euroling Acquired by Episerver|url=http://www.vcpost.com/articles/8401/20130507/euroling-acquired-episerver.htm|website=Venture Capital Post|accessdate=May 7, 2013|ref=References}}</ref> * January 27, 2015: Episerver merged with Ektron, a New Hampshire-based CMS company.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}} * August 31, 2016: Episerver acquired London-based Peerius, an omnichannel commerce personalization engine.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}} * October 1st, 2016 Episerver acquired Berlin-based Optivo, an email-marketing automation service provider.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}
