{{term|term= '''[[Biophysics]]'''}}{{defn|defn= Is an interdisciplinary science that applies approaches and methods traditionally used in [[physics]] to study [[Biology|biological]] phenomena.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/biophysics|title=Biophysics {{!}} science|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-07-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhou HX | title = Q&A: What is biophysics? | journal = BMC Biology | volume = 9 | pages = 13 | date = March 2011 | pmid = 21371342 | pmc = 3055214 | doi = 10.1186/1741-7007-9-13 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/biophysics|title=the definition of biophysics|website=www.dictionary.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref> Biophysics covers all scales of [[biological organization]], from [[Molecule|molecular]] to [[organism]]ic and [[Population (biology)|populations]]. Biophysical research shares significant overlap with [[biochemistry]], [[molecular biology]], [[physical chemistry]], [[physiology]], [[nanotechnology]], [[bioengineering]], [[computational biology]], [[biomechanics]] and [[systems biology]].}}
{{term|term= '''[[Biot number]]'''}}{{defn|defn=The '''Biot number''' ('''Bi''') is a [[dimensionless quantity]] used in heat transfer calculations. It is named after the eighteenth century French physicist [[Jean-Baptiste Biot]] (1774–1862), and gives a simple index of the ratio of the heat transfer resistances ''inside of'' and ''at the surface of'' a body. This ratio determines whether or not the temperatures inside a body will vary significantly in space, while the body heats or cools over time, from a thermal gradient applied to its surface.}}
{{term|term= '''[[Block and tackle]]'''}}{{defn|defn=A  system of pulleys and a rope threaded between them, used to lift or pull heavy loads.}}
{{term|term= '''[[Body force]]'''}}{{defn|defn=Is a force that acts throughout the volume of a body. Forces due to [[gravity]], [[electrostatics|electric fields]] and [[magnetic fields]] are examples of body forces. Body forces contrast with [[contact force]]s or [[surface force]]s which are exerted to the surface of an object..}}
{{term|term= '''[[Boiler]]'''}}{{defn|defn=A device whose purpose is to add heat to a working fluid to vaporise it..}} 
