{{term|term= '''[[Dalton's law]]'''}}{{defn|defn=In [[chemistry]] and [[physics]], '''Dalton's law''' (also called '''Dalton's law of partial pressures''') states that in a mixture of non-reacting gases, the total  [[pressure]] exerted is equal to the sum of the [[partial pressure]]s of the individual gases.<ref name="Silberberg">{{cite book |last=Silberberg |first=Martin S. |date=2009 |title=Chemistry: the molecular nature of matter and change |edition=5th |publisher=McGraw-Hill |location=Boston |isbn=9780073048598 |page=206 |ref=1}}</ref>.}}
