{{term|term= '''[[Differential pulley]]'''}}{{defn|defn=A '''differential pulley''', also called '''Weston differential pulley''',  or colloquially '''chain fall''', is used to manually lift very heavy objects like [[Internal combustion engine|car engines]]. It is operated by pulling upon the slack section of a continuous chain that wraps around pulleys. The relative size of two connected pulleys determines the maximum weight that can be lifted by hand. The load will remain in place (and not lower under the force of [[gravity]]) until the chain is pulled.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Macauley |first1=David |last2=Ardley |first2=Neil |title=The New Way Things Work |page=56 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company |location=Boston, USA |year=1998 |isbn=0-395-93847-3}}</ref>.}}
