{{term|term= '''[[Distance]]'''}}{{defn|defn=.}}
{{term|term= '''[[Doppler effect]]'''}}{{defn|defn=The '''Doppler effect''' (or the '''Doppler shift''') is the change in [[frequency]] or [[wavelength]] of a [[wave]] in relation to an [[observer (physics)|observer]] who is moving relative to the wave source.<ref name="Giordano">{{cite book
 | last1  = Giordano
 | first1 = Nicholas
 | title  = College Physics: Reasoning and Relationships
 | publisher = Cengage Learning
 | date   = 2009
 | pages  = 421–424
 | url    = https://books.google.com/books?id=BwistUlpZ7cC&pg=PA424
 | isbn   = 978-0534424718
 }}</ref> It is named after the [[Austria]]n physicist [[Christian Doppler]], who described the phenomenon in 1842.}}
