'''Roger & Gallet''' (also '''Roger et Gallet''') is a [[France|French]] [[perfume]] [[company]] founded by merchant [[Charles Armand Roger]] and banker [[Charles Martial Gallet]] in 1862. They purchased a [[Paris|Parisian]] perfumery business founded in 1806 by Jean Marie Joseph Farina, grand-grand-nephew of [[Johann Maria Farina|Giovanni Maria Farina]], the creator of [[Eau de Cologne]]. Roger & Gallet then won a legal dispute over the right to use the Farina family name, and the company now owns the rights to ''Eau de Cologne extra vieille'', in contrast to the ''Original Eau de Cologne'' from [[Cologne]]. 

Roger & Gallet specialized in [[Soap|toilet soap]] which was produced in a large factory near Paris. The company made a name for itself with its luxurious bath soaps, which in 1879 first appeared in their signature round shape, with the crinkled silk paper and seal, still in use today. Later, they proved successful with the newly synthesized fragrance of [[Viola odorata|violet]], for which they held the French rights, producing perfumes such as ''[[Vera Violetta]]''.<ref>{{citation|title=Beauty Imagined|year=2010|author=Geoffrey Jones|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-160961-9}}</ref>

In 1975, Roger & Gallet was acquired by the [[Sanofi|Sanofi Group]], who in turn sold the brand to [[Gucci]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1999-11-16/business/9911150732_1_yves-saint-networking-products-gucci|title=Gucci Will Buy Sanofi, Yves Saint Laurent Owner|last=|first=|date=|work=Orlando Sentinel|access-date=2018-05-27|publication-date=November 16, 1999|language=en}}</ref> L'Oreal acquired Roger & Gallet from Gucci, a subsidiary at that time of [[Pinault Printemps Redoute|PPR]], in 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-features/ppr-l-oreal-complete-ysl-deal-1022296/|title=PPR, L’Oreal Complete YSL Deal|last=Staff|first=WWD|date=2008-05-01|work=WWD|access-date=2018-05-27|language=en-US}}</ref>

